        <hl1>In Lawn Mower Races, the Loser Is Earth</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ilya Fischhoff letter on June 12 front page article on growing infatuation of American men with lawn mower races; says mower racing is colossal waste of gasoline; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Gentlemen, Start Your Lawn Mower Engines'' (front page, June 12), about the growing infatuation of American men with lawn mower races:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Gentlemen, Start Your Lawn Mower Engines'' (front page, June 12), about the growing infatuation of American men with lawn mower races:</p>
        <p>Mower racing -- combined with the racing of cars, trucks, tractors and the like -- is a colossal waste of gasoline. Gasoline is a limited resource, prone to spilling in pristine places. When burned, gasoline releases pollutants, including those that cause global climate change.</p>
        <p>Could we apply our creativity to entertainments that don't celebrate the internal combustion engine?</p>
        <p>ILYA FISCHHOFF  Pittsburgh, June 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
